    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1950-07-31T05:30:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1950-07-31T05:30:00-05:00" n="381"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d381">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">795B.00/7–3150: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in India</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Henderson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                        <lb/>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">priority</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">New Delhi</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1950-07-31T16:00:00+05:30"
                            >July 31, 1950—4 p. m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received July 31—8:56 p. m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>254. 1. Bajpai, SYG <gloss target="#t_MEA1">MEA</gloss> told me today he hoped US
                    would not be disappointed at size and composition <gloss target="#t_GOI1"
                        >GOI</gloss> “token force” for Korea.<note n="1" xml:id="d381fn1">See U.N.
                        document S/1647, dated July 29, 1950.</note> It was contemplated that
                    medical unit would comprise between 200 and 300 persons carefully selected from
                    defense forces who would serve as military contingent in uniform. Among them
                    would be some of best surgeons in India. It was regretted that <gloss
                        target="#t_GOI1">GOI</gloss> had no combat units available at present, but
                    hoped medical unit could be of help.</p>
                <p>2. I told Bajpai that I was sure <gloss target="#t_GOI1">GOI</gloss> contribution
                    would be appreciated. I had had some experience with Indian military doctors and
                    considered that they stood extremely high in their profession.</p>
                <p>3. It would be helpful if indication could be made through appropriate channel to
                        <gloss target="#t_GOI1">GOI</gloss> of US appreciation of this aid. I regard
                    this contribution as only beginning. Meager as it is, announcement has given
                    rise considerable criticism from Indian press. Decision represents in present
                    atmosphere courageous act on part <gloss target="#t_GOI1">GOI</gloss>.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Henderson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
